      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1811_06_30_page01.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <dateline><!--If there's no date line, omit this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                  <name type="place" ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE"/>Edgeworthstown, Ireland
                        <date when="1811-06-30"/>June 30, 1811</dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>
                            My Dear Sir<lb/>
                     <!-- Use if letter has a saluation ("Dear Sir," for example). If not, delete this line.-->
                  </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>The business and<lb/>
                    pleasures of London for this<lb/>
                    year draw towards a <choice>
                  <orig>conclu-<lb/>
                        sion</orig>
                  <reg>conclusion</reg>
               </choice> and our season for <choice>
                  <orig>im-<lb/>
                  </orig>
                  <reg>
                     <hi rend="underline">improvement</hi>
                  </reg>
               </choice> which is the<lb/>
                    business and the pleasure of <add>this house</add>
               <lb/>
                    has begun - I do not mean<lb/>
                    to remind you of a <hi rend="underline">promise</hi>
               <lb/>
                    but merely to say that our<lb/>
                    house will for some time<lb/>
                    be at our own disposal &amp;<lb/>
                    that none of us are engaged<lb/>
                    from home<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>We cannot however refrain<lb/>
                    from saying that the oftener<lb/>
                    we <hi rend="underline">hear</hi> from you, the more<lb/>
                    we desire to see you<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>yours truly<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">Rich<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> Lovell Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
               <!-- Begin transcibing the body of the letter here. -->
            </p>
            <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1811_06_30_page02.jpg"/>
            <p>Mr dear Sir, My <persName ref="./Personograph.xml#EdgeR1">father</persName> flatters me that the<lb/>
                    expression of my wish to see you here, may<lb/>
                    add to the inducements <add>by which</add> he has endeavored<lb/>
                    to draw you to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName> - I can only repeat<lb/>
                    the simple truth - that I do earnestly wish<lb/>
                    to see in all the leisure of English domestic<lb/>
                    intimacy one of whose abilities I have formed<lb/>
                    such a high opinion, &amp; of whose kindness &amp;<lb/>
                    friendship we have received so many proofs.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Your labors for the press are finished,<lb/>
                    are they not? - You say you are not engaged<lb/>
                    in politics - You are above making common<lb/>
                    place excuses, especially to friends - then<lb/>
                    what can prevent your coming to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName>?<lb/>
                    - Surely not the dread of 8 hours sea-sickness.<lb/>
                    - The moment you land in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin_IE">Dublin</placeName> you<lb/>
                    can find a public mail coach as comfortable<lb/>
                    as any in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">England</placeName>, which will bring you to<lb/>
                    our gate in one day's time - Or if you prefer<lb/>
                    travelling by water we have a canal boat<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1811_06_30_page03.jpg"/>
                    which will bring you within 12 miles of us, where<lb/>
                    our carriage should meet you - I enter into<lb/>
                    detail because I have often [insertion]known[/insertion] great schemes<lb/>
                    fail for want of minor arrangements.<lb/>
                    - you shall have complete leisure &amp; command of your time.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>My father is this day going to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin_IE">Dublin</placeName>
               <lb/>
                    to attend a Board of Education and to lay<lb/>
                    before them a Plan for the education of the<lb/>
                    poor in this country, which I know will<lb/>
                    not be relished either by Bishops or <choice>
                  <orig>Archbi<lb/>
                        shops</orig>
                  <reg>Archbshiops</reg>
               </choice>, but which I think <hi rend="underline">you</hi> would approve<lb/>
                    and which may perhaps please the liberal<lb/>
                    part of the English public - but <hi rend="underline">he</hi> and <hi rend="underline">it</hi>
               <unclear>w</unclear>
               <lb/>
                    be heartily abused in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName> by the <choice>
                  <orig>Pro<lb/>
                        testant</orig>
                  <reg>Protestant</reg>
               </choice> ascendancy party- and by a vast <lb/>
                    majority who think that the people can be<lb/>
                    driven best <del>in the dark</del>
               <add>hoodwinked</add>  - Woe be to the <choice>
                  <orig>coach-<lb/>
                        men</orig>
                  <reg>coachmen</reg>
               </choice> who persist in driving upon this belief<lb/>
                    horses, who have now learnt their strength.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Come and converse with &amp; we can go over <lb/>
                    in five minutes more subjects than 5 hours<lb/>
                    or 5 days writing could <del>may</del> comprise.<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
                    Your obliged<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
               <!--include linebreaks, if used. example: <closer> Yours<lb/> Very sincerely<lb/> -->
            </closer>
